to write so the Hong Kong government will listen ","contentHtml":"<h2>The need to pressure the government to deal with neighbourhood issues</h2><p>Like most people living in modern cities, as Hong Kong residents, we have the right to expect efficient and effective services from the government, especially since we pay taxes to fund these services. However, in reality, we often encounter problems in our neighborhoods that go unresolved despite repeated requests to the government. Sometimes, we need to apply pressure to get the government staff to do their job. The key to getting the government to listen is to know whom to contact to make requests and how to frame a problem to ensure the staff will take action. In this post, we will explore a&nbsp;case study&nbsp;that demonstrates how to apply these principles to get the government to listen to our concerns and take action. </p><h2>Case study of&nbsp;272A bus&nbsp;in my neighbourhood</h2><p>On Saturday, 29 Apr, 2023, I found that a significant number of&nbsp;construction site workers&nbsp;in&nbsp;Pak Shek Kok (where I live)&nbsp;need to return home. However, the one double-decker bus that services the area is often unable to accommodate all of them, leading to long waits for the next bus. This is not only inconvenient for the workers but also causes trouble to other residents living in the neighbourhood. A simple solution to this problem is to increase the frequency of the bus. </p><figure class=\"slate-resizable-image-embed slate-image-embed__resize-full-width\"><img alt=\"No alt text provided for this image\" data-media-urn=\"\" data-li-src=\"https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/D5612AQEi6j-Ggoq3TA/article-inline_image-shrink_1500_2232/article-inline_image-shrink_1500_2232/0/1683979308401?e=1760572800&amp;v=beta&amp;t=VdHHvEo5p2VOuX2jViYQhBrFitvZQFiXcolp6ReJkAI\" src=\"//:0\"></figure><p>To address this issue, there are four options: </p><ol><li>write to the&nbsp;bus company&nbsp;</li><li>write to the&nbsp;Transport Department&nbsp;that supervises the bus company</li><li>call the bus company </li><li>call the Transport Department </li></ol><h3>Whom to contact? Writing or phone call?</h3><p>When faced with the issue of overcrowding on public transportation, it's important to address the issue through the appropriate channels. While calling the bus company or writing to them directly may seem like a straightforward solution, these options may not always be the most effective. Here's why:</p><p>1. No written record: Contacting the bus company by phone may not leave a written record of the conversation, which can make it difficult to follow up on the issue later. Without a written record, it's harder to hold the bus company accountable if they fail to take action to address the issue. The same is true for calling the government staff. </p><p>2. Limited response: Bus companies may not be incentivized to take action on complaints received from individuals, and may not have the resources to address the issue on their own. As a result, writing to the bus company may not result in a satisfactory resolution to the issue.</p><p>3. Supervision: On the other hand, the Transport Department that supervises the bus company is responsible for ensuring that public transportation is safe and accessible for all. As a government agency, the Transport Department staff is expected to follow up on complaints received from the public and take appropriate action. In addition, the department is accountable to more senior staff, the Ombudsman, and other oversight agencies, which can provide additional pressure to address the issue.</p><p>Overall, writing to the Transport Department that supervises the bus company is the best option for addressing the issue of overcrowding on public transportation. It ensures that there is a written record of the complaint, that the responsible agency is held accountable, and that there is a higher likelihood of a satisfactory resolution to the issue.</p><h3>Threaten to complain: an effective way to persuade the government to take actions</h3><p>I emailed the Transport Department the same day (29 Apr) I identified the problem. </p><p><em>Referring to the picture attached (taken around 5pm today), please kindly review occupancy rate data on Saturday afternoons. KMB should deploy an additional bus to serve the workers from the construction site if the surging demand is expected every Saturday. @1823_general@1823.gov.hk could you inform us if there is a government-funded construction project in Pak Shek Kok? Grateful if this case is followed up promptly.</em></p><p>Unfortunately, a week later on 6 May, the problem remained unresolved. This is somewhat expected as the Hong Kong government is not very efficient in dealing with these matters. But I paid the visit to the bus stop on that Saturday (6 May) and took a few more pictures. Armed with the evidence, I wrote to the Transport Department again. </p><p><em>Dear Sir/Madam</em></p><p><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I paid a visit to Pak Shek Kok bus station for&nbsp;272A&nbsp;and the next stop at St Martin this afternoon. As shown in the attached pictures, the bus was fully loaded at Pak Shek Kok; some passengers could not board the bus at St Martin. The bus was extremely crowded, which may raise safety concerns. I hope this matter can be addressed as soon as possible. I'll visit the site again next&nbsp;Saturday. If the situation is not improved by then, I'll have to refer the case to&nbsp;more&nbsp;senior staff in your department as well as other agencies supervising the department.</em></p><p><em>Yours sincerely</em></p><p><em>Simon Wang</em></p><figure class=\"slate-resizable-image-embed slate-image-embed__resize-full-width\"><img alt=\"No alt text provided for this image\" data-media-urn=\"\" data-li-src=\"https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/D5612AQF6dX3QzX43nw/article-inline_image-shrink_1500_2232/article-inline_image-shrink_1500_2232/0/1683985762106?e=1759968000&amp;v=beta&amp;t=i2I5g0i8rgBnVeqzukUbnDCAqZMm8NRenNOFINeLrUo\" src=\"//:0\"><figcaption>Many construction site workers waiting for 272A bus on Saturday afternoons</figcaption></figure><figure class=\"slate-resizable-image-embed slate-image-embed__resize-full-width\"><img alt=\"No alt text provided for this image\" data-media-urn=\"\" data-li-src=\"https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/D5612AQE3IFaT1-JvZA/article-inline_image-shrink_1500_2232/article-inline_image-shrink_1500_2232/0/1683985860745?e=1759968000&amp;v=beta&amp;t=dcAA7NXzQjmA-LmmE8Z5Y0fXIoeDKnD07wLLoxYZ8-M\" src=\"//:0\"><figcaption>Some passengers cannot board the bus that was already overloaded</figcaption></figure><p>By Thursday 11 May, I have not heard from the Transport Department and decided that the police should be alerted. So I wrote to the Tai Po Office of Hong Kong Police by looking up to the Telephone Directory of the Hong Kong government https://tel.directory.gov.hk/index_HKPF_ENG.html </p><figure class=\"slate-resizable-image-embed slate-image-embed__resize-full-width\"><img alt=\"No alt text provided for this image\" data-media-urn=\"\" data-li-src=\"https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/D5612AQFO648UVRi2_g/article-inline_image-shrink_1500_2232/article-inline_image-shrink_1500_2232/0/1683986154244?e=1759968000&amp;v=beta&amp;t=r6jJG6tZK22Ulmxa71VrygRlte-VgpVJ_WsAsnBXdds\" src=\"//:0\"><figcaption>Through the Government Telephone Directory, you can find contact info of senior government staff.</figcaption></figure><p>In my email to Dist Commander (Tai Po) and Div Commander (Tai Po), I asked the staff to investigate the case and keep a written record. </p><p><em>Dear Tai Po division office of HKPF</em></p><p><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Referring to my email regarding&nbsp;272A&nbsp;bus in Pak Shek Kok and St Martin&nbsp;on&nbsp;Saturday&nbsp;afternoons, the potential problem of bus overloading merits your attention. I am not sure if an additional bus will be deployed at 5pm this coming&nbsp;Saturday. Grateful if your office can look into this matter and keep a written record in case Ombudsman and senior staff of your department will review it later.</em></p><p><em>Yours sincerely&nbsp;</em></p><p><em>Simon Wang</em></p><h3>The government responded to the appropriate incentives </h3><p>On 13 May, the third Saturday since I identified the problem, I visited the bus stop again and found that a number of police officers were on the site to inspect the bus and ensure it was not overloaded. While the 272A bus leaving Pak Shek Kok around 5pm was full, another 272A bus will arrive in about 5 minutes (instead of 20 minutes) thanks to Transport Department staff's follow-up with the bus company. </p><figure class=\"slate-resizable-image-embed slate-image-embed__resize-full-width\"><img alt=\"No alt text provided for this image\" data-media-urn=\"\" data-li-src=\"https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/D5612AQFeuQO8oCK7_Q/article-inline_image-shrink_1500_2232/article-inline_image-shrink_1500_2232/0/1683986729329?e=1759968000&amp;v=beta&amp;t=qFbHZ9hXXxRMp18rSn1oFPvO74GGs1czWseujwqu3n4\" src=\"//:0\"><figcaption>Police officers were on site on 13 May</figcaption></figure><h2>Reflections on the case </h2><p>Here are the four key takeaways from the case: </p><ol><li><strong>Advocacy</strong>: By recognizing the needs of the community and speaking up on behalf of those who may not have a voice, individuals can make a difference in their neighbourhoods. In this case, construction site workers do not often speak up and fight for their rights and their needs might be neglected. </li><li><strong>Communication</strong>: Knowing whom to contact and how to frame a problem effectively can be key to getting the government to listen and take action. Students can learn how to access government resources, such as telephone directories, to find the right people to contact and make their voices heard. To persuade the Transport Department and the Police Department to take actions, different arguments have to be made. </li><li><strong>Accountability</strong>: It is important to learn that there are channels for filing complaints and holding government officials accountable, such as the Ombudsman and senior staff of relevant departments. By learning how to use these channels, we can advocate for changes in their communities and ensure that their concerns are addressed.</li><li><strong>Persuasion</strong>: Building strong arguments and providing evidence to support requests for action can be an effective way to persuade government officials to take action. We can learn how to make&nbsp;compelling arguments&nbsp;that highlight the need for change and the potential benefits of taking action.</li></ol><p>In summary, this incident demonstrates how ordinary people can make a difference by advocating for change in their neighbourhoods and pressuring the government to take action. By learning from this case and developing skills in&nbsp;advocacy, communication, accountability, and persuasion, students can become effective agents of change in their communities. </p><p><br></p><h2>A conversation among the police, the Transport Department and the bus company simulated by ChatGPT </h2><ul><li>Mr. Leung:&nbsp;Police Officer&nbsp;from the Tai Po Police Division</li><li>Ms. Yuen: Representative from the Transport Department</li><li>Mr. Cheung: Representative from the&nbsp;KMB Bus Company</li></ul><iframe frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" src=\"about:blank\" width=\"720\" height=\"169\" title=\"Poe\" data-li-src=\"https://www.linkedin.com/embeds/publishingEmbed.html?articleId=7742804303864460767&amp;li_theme=light\"></iframe><p>Mr. Leung: Good afternoon, Ms. Yuen and Mr. Cheung. Thank you for joining me today to discuss the issue of overcrowding on the&nbsp;272A bus&nbsp;in Pak Shek Kok.</p><p>Ms. Yuen: Good afternoon, Mr. Leung. We appreciate your interest in this issue and are happy to work together to find a solution.</p><p>Mr. Cheung: Yes, thank you for having us. We understand the concerns raised by Mr. Wang and are willing to work with the government to address the issue.</p><p>Mr. Leung: Great. So, Ms. Yuen, can you provide an update on what actions the&nbsp;Transport Department&nbsp;is taking to address this issue?</p><p>Ms. Yuen: Yes, we have received Mr. Wang's emails and have been in contact with KMB to discuss potential solutions. We have agreed to deploy an additional bus at 5 PM on Saturdays to help alleviate the overcrowding. However, we have not yet inspected the site to assess the situation firsthand.</p><p>Mr. Leung: I see. Mr. Cheung, can you speak to KMB's efforts to address this issue?</p><p>Mr. Cheung: Certainly, Mr. Leung. We are also willing to work with the government to find additional solutions if necessary.</p><p>Mr. Leung: Thank you both for your updates. I think it would be helpful for the police to inspect the site next Saturday afternoon to assess the situation and ensure the safety of the passengers. Ms. Yuen, can you coordinate with the police to arrange for an inspection?</p><p>Ms. Yuen: Yes, of course. We will work with the police to arrange for an inspection next Saturday afternoon.</p><p>Mr. Cheung: In the meantime, we could consider deploying the additional bus 6 minutes after the bus at&nbsp;5 PM&nbsp;instead of waiting for 20 minutes. This could help alleviate the overcrowding and ensure that passengers do not have to wait too long for the next bus.</p><p>Ms. Yuen: That's a good idea, Mr. Cheung. We could implement this change immediately while we continue to work on a long-term solution.</p><p>Mr. Leung: Excellent. It sounds like we have a plan to address the issue of overcrowding on the 272A bus. How to write so the Hong Kong government will listen

Simon Ho Wang

Empower university students to make a difference in our communities with writing and research skills
May 13, 2023

The need to pressure the government to deal with neighbourhood issues

Like most people living in modern cities, as Hong Kong residents, we have the right to expect efficient and effective services from the government, especially since we pay taxes to fund these services. However, in reality, we often encounter problems in our neighborhoods that go unresolved despite repeated requests to the government. Sometimes, we need to apply pressure to get the government staff to do their job. The key to getting the government to listen is to know whom to contact to make requests and how to frame a problem to ensure the staff will take action. In this post, we will explore a case study that demonstrates how to apply these principles to get the government to listen to our concerns and take action.

Case study of 272A bus in my neighbourhood

On Saturday, 29 Apr, 2023, I found that a significant number of construction site workers in Pak Shek Kok (where I live) need to return home. However, the one double-decker bus that services the area is often unable to accommodate all of them, leading to long waits for the next bus. This is not only inconvenient for the workers but also causes trouble to other residents living in the neighbourhood. A simple solution to this problem is to increase the frequency of the bus.

To address this issue, there are four options:

  1. write to the bus company
  2. write to the Transport Department that supervises the bus company
  3. call the bus company
  4. call the Transport Department

Whom to contact? Writing or phone call?

When faced with the issue of overcrowding on public transportation, it's important to address the issue through the appropriate channels. While calling the bus company or writing to them directly may seem like a straightforward solution, these options may not always be the most effective. Here's why:

1. No written record: Contacting the bus company by phone may not leave a written record of the conversation, which can make it difficult to follow up on the issue later. Without a written record, it's harder to hold the bus company accountable if they fail to take action to address the issue. The same is true for calling the government staff.

2. Limited response: Bus companies may not be incentivized to take action on complaints received from individuals, and may not have the resources to address the issue on their own. As a result, writing to the bus company may not result in a satisfactory resolution to the issue.

3. Supervision: On the other hand, the Transport Department that supervises the bus company is responsible for ensuring that public transportation is safe and accessible for all. As a government agency, the Transport Department staff is expected to follow up on complaints received from the public and take appropriate action. In addition, the department is accountable to more senior staff, the Ombudsman, and other oversight agencies, which can provide additional pressure to address the issue.

Overall, writing to the Transport Department that supervises the bus company is the best option for addressing the issue of overcrowding on public transportation. It ensures that there is a written record of the complaint, that the responsible agency is held accountable, and that there is a higher likelihood of a satisfactory resolution to the issue.

Threaten to complain: an effective way to persuade the government to take actions

I emailed the Transport Department the same day (29 Apr) I identified the problem.

Referring to the picture attached (taken around 5pm today), please kindly review occupancy rate data on Saturday afternoons. KMB should deploy an additional bus to serve the workers from the construction site if the surging demand is expected every Saturday. @1823_general@1823.gov.hk could you inform us if there is a government-funded construction project in Pak Shek Kok? Grateful if this case is followed up promptly.

Unfortunately, a week later on 6 May, the problem remained unresolved. This is somewhat expected as the Hong Kong government is not very efficient in dealing with these matters. But I paid the visit to the bus stop on that Saturday (6 May) and took a few more pictures. Armed with the evidence, I wrote to the Transport Department again.

Dear Sir/Madam

I paid a visit to Pak Shek Kok bus station for 272A and the next stop at St Martin this afternoon. As shown in the attached pictures, the bus was fully loaded at Pak Shek Kok; some passengers could not board the bus at St Martin. The bus was extremely crowded, which may raise safety concerns. I hope this matter can be addressed as soon as possible. I'll visit the site again next Saturday. If the situation is not improved by then, I'll have to refer the case to more senior staff in your department as well as other agencies supervising the department.

Yours sincerely

Simon Wang

By Thursday 11 May, I have not heard from the Transport Department and decided that the police should be alerted. So I wrote to the Tai Po Office of Hong Kong Police by looking up to the Telephone Directory of the Hong Kong government https://tel.directory.gov.hk/index_HKPF_ENG.html

In my email to Dist Commander (Tai Po) and Div Commander (Tai Po), I asked the staff to investigate the case and keep a written record.

Dear Tai Po division office of HKPF

Referring to my email regarding 272A bus in Pak Shek Kok and St Martin on Saturday afternoons, the potential problem of bus overloading merits your attention. I am not sure if an additional bus will be deployed at 5pm this coming Saturday. Grateful if your office can look into this matter and keep a written record in case Ombudsman and senior staff of your department will review it later.

Yours sincerely

Simon Wang

The government responded to the appropriate incentives

On 13 May, the third Saturday since I identified the problem, I visited the bus stop again and found that a number of police officers were on the site to inspect the bus and ensure it was not overloaded. While the 272A bus leaving Pak Shek Kok around 5pm was full, another 272A bus will arrive in about 5 minutes (instead of 20 minutes) thanks to Transport Department staff's follow-up with the bus company.

Reflections on the case

Here are the four key takeaways from the case:

  1. Advocacy: By recognizing the needs of the community and speaking up on behalf of those who may not have a voice, individuals can make a difference in their neighbourhoods. In this case, construction site workers do not often speak up and fight for their rights and their needs might be neglected.
  2. Communication: Knowing whom to contact and how to frame a problem effectively can be key to getting the government to listen and take action. Students can learn how to access government resources, such as telephone directories, to find the right people to contact and make their voices heard. To persuade the Transport Department and the Police Department to take actions, different arguments have to be made.
  3. Accountability: It is important to learn that there are channels for filing complaints and holding government officials accountable, such as the Ombudsman and senior staff of relevant departments. By learning how to use these channels, we can advocate for changes in their communities and ensure that their concerns are addressed.
  4. Persuasion: Building strong arguments and providing evidence to support requests for action can be an effective way to persuade government officials to take action. We can learn how to make compelling arguments that highlight the need for change and the potential benefits of taking action.

In summary, this incident demonstrates how ordinary people can make a difference by advocating for change in their neighbourhoods and pressuring the government to take action. By learning from this case and developing skills in advocacy, communication, accountability, and persuasion, students can become effective agents of change in their communities.


A conversation among the police, the Transport Department and the bus company simulated by ChatGPT

  • Mr. Leung: Police Officer from the Tai Po Police Division
  • Ms. Yuen: Representative from the Transport Department
  • Mr. Cheung: Representative from the KMB Bus Company

Mr. Leung: Good afternoon, Ms. Yuen and Mr. Cheung. Thank you for joining me today to discuss the issue of overcrowding on the 272A bus in Pak Shek Kok.

Ms. Yuen: Good afternoon, Mr. Leung. We appreciate your interest in this issue and are happy to work together to find a solution.

Mr. Cheung: Yes, thank you for having us. We understand the concerns raised by Mr. Wang and are willing to work with the government to address the issue.

Mr. Leung: Great. So, Ms. Yuen, can you provide an update on what actions the Transport Department is taking to address this issue?

Ms. Yuen: Yes, we have received Mr. Wang's emails and have been in contact with KMB to discuss potential solutions. We have agreed to deploy an additional bus at 5 PM on Saturdays to help alleviate the overcrowding. However, we have not yet inspected the site to assess the situation firsthand.

Mr. Leung: I see. Mr. Cheung, can you speak to KMB's efforts to address this issue?

Mr. Cheung: Certainly, Mr. Leung. We have been in contact with the Transport Department and have agreed to deploy an additional bus at 5 PM on Saturdays. We are also willing to work with the government to find additional solutions if necessary.

Mr. Leung: Thank you both for your updates. I think it would be helpful for the police to inspect the site next Saturday afternoon to assess the situation and ensure the safety of the passengers. Ms. Yuen, can you coordinate with the police to arrange for an inspection?

Ms. Yuen: Yes, of course. We will work with the police to arrange for an inspection next Saturday afternoon.

Mr. Cheung: In the meantime, we could consider deploying the additional bus 6 minutes after the bus at 5 PM instead of waiting for 20 minutes. This could help alleviate the overcrowding and ensure that passengers do not have to wait too long for the next bus.

Ms. Yuen: That's a good idea, Mr. Cheung. We could implement this change immediately while we continue to work on a long-term solution.

Mr. Leung: Excellent. It sounds like we have a plan to address the issue of overcrowding on the 272A bus. Thank you both for your cooperation and efforts to ensure the safety and comfort of the passengers.
